ing, but X in dut_vector will only match X.\nassign tb_match = ( { next_state_ref, out_ref } === ( { next_state_ref, out_ref } ^ { next_state_dut, out_dut } ^ { next_state_ref, out_ref } ) );\n// Use explicit sensitivity list here. @(*) causes NetProc::nex_input() to be called when trying to compute\n// the sensitivity list of the @(strobe) process, which isn't implemented.\nalways @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\tstats1.clocks++;\n\tif (!tb_match) begin\n\t\tif (stats1.errors == 0) stats1.errortime = $time;\n\t\tstats1.errors++;\n\tend\n\tif (next_state_ref !== ( next_state_ref ^ next_state_dut ^ next_state_ref ))\n\tbegin if (stats1.errors_next_state == 0) stats1.errortime_next_state = $time;\n\t\tstats1.errors_next_state = stats1.errors_next_state+1'b1; end\n\tif (out_ref !== ( out_ref ^ out_dut ^ out_ref ))\n\tbegin if (stats1.errors_out == 0) stats1.errortime_out = $time;\n\t\tstats1.errors_out = stats1.errors_out+1'b1; end\n\t\nend\n\ndisplay \"Simulation PASSED\" if no mismatch occurs, otherwise display:\n\"SIMULATION FAILED - x MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME y\".\nWhen simulating the code, keep track of input and output signals using queues and store them if a mismatch is found. Display the stored data when a mismatch occurs.\n\nDisplay for the FIRST mismatch, while maintaining the original logic of error counting.\n\nRemember to declare all ports as logic and always generate the complete testbench, no matter how long it is.\nRemember to follow the requirements above and generate a valid JSON object."
